{{Infobox Website | name = MaYoMo | logo = Mayomo logo.jpg | screenshot = MaYoMo screenshot.png | screenshot_size = 250px | caption = Map Your Moments | url = {{URL|https://web.archive.org/web/20121117080139/http://www.mayomo.com/|mayomo.com}} {{small|(archived)}} | commercial = | type = [[Citizen journalism]] | registration = | owner = MaYoMo B.V. | creator = | launch date = 2009 | current status = }}
'''MaYoMo''' was a [[user-generated]] news site for mobile [[citizen journalism]]. MaYoMo.com, short for "'''Ma'''p '''Yo'''ur '''Mo'''ments", was officially launched in October 2009. The site was owned by MaYoMo B.V., which is based in [[Amsterdam]], the [[Netherlands]].
==Features==
Global news and local stories by the site's community of contributors was [[geolocate]]d on an interactive world map, depending on the place they have happened. With an "Ask for News" option users could request news and information about particular events from any place of the world .<ref name="journalism.co.uk">[http://www.journalism.co.uk/staging/5/articles/536405.php Mayomo: A global mission for user-generated news], ''www.journalism.co.uk''.</ref> The news content was ordered at a [[timeline]], according to its date of action. One could set the time indicator to any year and date between the year 1895 and 2100 for a narrower search criteria.<ref name="Chicago Flame">[http://media.www.chicagoflame.com/media/storage/paper519/news/2009/10/26/Features/Mayomo.News.Has.A.New.Face-3812371.shtml MaYoMo: News has a new face], ''Chicago Flame''.</ref> Users could comment and also rank on a scale from 1 to 5 on each news submission.
MaYoMo hosted user-generated video news about [[virtual world]]s like [[Lineage II]], [[Half-Life (series)|Half-Life]], [[World of Warcraft]], [[FIFA]], [[Second Life]], etc., on "[http://www.mayomo.com/virtu Virtu]", a so-called virtual continent, placed between [[North America]] and [[Africa]].<ref name="Chicago Flame" />
In February 2010, MaYoMo had 60,000 videos from 130 countries.<ref name="San Francisco Chronicle">[http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2010/02/19/BU321C3727.DTL Amateur video wins prestigious journalism award], ''San Francisco Chronicle''.</ref> The site was available in 11 languages: [[Arabic language|Arabic]], [[English language|English]], [[French language|French]], [[German language|German]], [[Greek language|Greek]], [[Italian language|Italian]], [[Japanese language|Japanese]], [[Simplified Chinese|Simplified Mandarin]], [[Traditional Chinese|Traditional Mandarin]], [[Russian language|Russian]], [[Spanish language|Spanish]].
